SIMPLE: pop
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pop
<hw>Pop</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of imitative origin. Cf.
<er>Poop</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small, sharp, quick explosive
sound or report; <as>as, to go off with a <ex>pop</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A nonalcoholic carbonated beverage; -- so called
because it expels the cork with a pop from the bottle containing it;
<as>as, ginger <ex>pop</ex>; lemon <ex>pop</ex>, etc.</as></def>
<rj><au>Hood.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> soda, soda pop, minerals.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European redwing.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pop corn</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Corn, or maize, of
peculiar excellence for popping; especially, a kind the grains of which
are small and compact</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Popped corn; corn which has
been popped.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pop
<hw>Pop</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Popped</conjf> <pr>(p⟦ocr⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Popping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a pop, or
sharp, quick sound; <as>as, the muskets <ex>popped</ex> away on all
sides</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enter, or issue forth, with a quick, sudden
movement; to move from place to place suddenly; to dart; -- with
<xex>in</xex>, <xex>out</xex>, <xex>upon</xex>, <xex>off</xex>,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that killed my king . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Popp'd</qex> in between the election and my hopes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A trick of <qex>popping</qex> up and down every moment.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To burst open with a pop, when heated over a fire;
<as>as, this corn <ex>pops</ex> well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pop
<hw>Pop</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To thrust or push
suddenly; to offer suddenly; to bring suddenly and unexpectedly to
notice; <as>as, to <ex>pop</ex> one's head in at the
door</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>popped</qex> a paper into his hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to pop; to cause to burst open by heat, as
grains of Indian corn; <as>as, to <ex>pop</ex> corn or
chestnuts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To eat or swallow; -- of food, especially snacks, in
small pieces; <as>as, he <ex>popped</ex> a whole can of peanuts while
watching the movie</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To pop off</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to thrust away, or
put off promptly; as, to <xex>pop</xex> one off with a denial.</cd>
<au>Locke.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to make a statement, or series of
statements, forcefully and in an opinionated manner; <as>as, he
<ex>popped off</ex> about his dislike of modern art</as>.</cd> --
<col><b>To pop the question</b></col>, <cd>to make an offer of marriage
to a lady.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <au>Dickens.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Pop
<hw>Pop</hw> <pr>(p⟦ocr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Like a pop;
suddenly; unexpectedly.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Pop</xex> goes his
plate.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>pop corn</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>popcorn</ent>⟦br⟧
